<a name="8.3"></a>
<h4>
  8.3:  Where is the  GAP file editor? How do I save
  GAP programs?
</h4>
<p>
GAP programs are simple text files, and you can edit them with
any text editor. Some editors may support GAP syntax highlighting and have 
other useful features:

<ul>

<li>
<p>
<a href="https://atom.io/">Atom</a>, with the
<a href="https://atom.io/packages/language-gap">language-gap</a>
package by <mixer person="Chris Jefferson" data="name_link"/>.
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="http://robrohan.com/projects/afae">Afae</a>,
a general purpose code editor for <a href="http://www.eclipse.org/Eclipse">Eclipse</a> (out-of-box)
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="http://www.barebones.com/products/bbedit/index.shtml">BBEdit</a> and
<a href="http://www.barebones.com/products/textwrangler/">TextWrangler</a>
(see below), using the
<a href="http://dev.quendi.de/gap/GAPLanguageModule.plist">syntax highlighting module</a>
by <mixer person="Max Horn" data="name_link"/>. To install it for TextWrangler,
first quit from the editor, then download the file
<a href="http://dev.quendi.de/gap/GAPLanguageModule.plist">GAPLanguageModule.plist</a>
and place it in the directory
<pre>
~/Library/Application Support/TextWrangler/Language Modules
</pre>
You will have to create this directory if it does not exist.
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/">emacs</a> 
(see <mixer manual="Reference: Editor Support">Editor Support</mixer>
and the 'etc' directory of the GAP installation,
and also the <a href="../Packages/Contrib/emacs.html">GAP mode for emacs</a>)
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="http://www.jedit.org/">jEdit</a> (exact configuration to be documented soon)
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="http://kate-editor.org/">Kate</a> (out-of-box)
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
<a href="https://notepad-plus-plus.org/">Notepad++</a> for Windows, using
<a href="http://dev.quendi.de/gap/gap.xml">syntax highlighting module</a>
by <mixer person="Max Horn" data="name_link"/>). To install, download the
<a href="http://dev.quendi.de/gap/gap.xml">gap.xml</a>, then select
"Define your language..." from the "Language" menu in Notepad++.
In the resulting dialog, click the "Import..." button.
This opens a file selector dialog, with which you should point to
the gap.xml file. After that close the "User Defined Language" dialog.
